01688101,0.15039530,0.03934913,0.02351353,0.06233982,-0.05532680,0.01212000,0.00247372,0.04633171,0.01449641,0.03787440,0.03793336,0.00811011,0.01223950,-0.04656970,0.04604026,0.01653275,0.03328760,-0.02515899,-0.03693525,-0.04804792,-0.00809088,0.02856666,0.03980402,0.00782676,-0.05762928,-0.09063213,-0.00538545,-0.02858087,-0.00239096,-0.07083049,-0.04993800,0.09039448,-0.00342473,0.02635781,0.03231933,-0.00633201,-0.03228022,-0.05747285,0.01797796,0.02272698,0.00342930,0.01033881,0.00897355]',E'API endpoint\n\nHTTP is commonly associated with REST, which uses "resources" as its core concept. In contrast, GraphQL''s conceptual model is an [entity graph](/learn/thinking-in-graphs/). As a result, entities in GraphQL are not identified by URLs. Instead, a GraphQL server operates on a single URL/endpoint, usually `/graphql`, and all GraphQL requests for a given service should be directed to this endpoint.','{"source": "graphql", "version": "1.0", "language": "graphql", "title": "Serving over HTTP", "section_title": "serving-over-httpx", "url": "https://github.com/graphql/graphql.github.io/blob/source/src/pages/learn/serving-over-http.mdx", "topics": "graphql,serving,over,httpx", "categories": "api,query,graphql"}');
