19,0.19610171,0.03356146,-0.01900991,0.07893063,0.02442703,-0.04597142,0.06619541,-0.02181634,0.03325132,0.02366448,0.10040624,0.03811428,0.03260047,-0.08504108,0.00156682,-0.01052200,-0.00627788,-0.01877322,-0.01615947,0.00322794,0.01136689,0.02749274,0.02102055,0.02777600,-0.07157098,-0.07161038,0.03366954,-0.02962015,-0.01150646,-0.05637818,-0.00545604,-0.02828015,-0.00201695,0.00895079,0.06330844,-0.00576548,-0.04174481,-0.00318667,0.03847324,-0.01530421,0.04116112,0.02499632,-0.06062219]',E'Body\n\nRegardless of the HTTP method used to send the query and variables, the response should be returned in the body of the request in JSON format. As mentioned in the GraphQL specification, a query might result in some data and some errors, and those should be returned in a JSON object of the form:\n\n```json\n{\n  "data": { ... },\n  "errors": [ ... ],\n  "extensions": { ... }\n}\n```\n\nIf no errors were returned, the `errors` field must not be present in the response. If errors occurred before execution could start, the `errors` field must include these errors and the `data` field must not be present in the response. The `extensions` field is optional and information provided here will be at the discretion of the GraphQL implementation.\n\nYou can read more about GraphQL spec-compliant response formats on the [Response page](/learn/response/).','{"source": "graphql", "version": "1.0", "language": "graphql", "title": "Serving over HTTP", "section_title": "serving-over-httpx", "url": "https://github.com/graphql/graphql.github.io/blob/source/src/pages/learn/serving-over-http.mdx", "topics": "graphql,serving,over,httpx", "categories": "api,query,graphql"}');
