161,0.22858205,0.00635541,0.05124398,0.05787772,-0.04417671,-0.02344253,-0.02872995,0.04717520,-0.00869723,-0.05550744,0.08964574,-0.01369308,0.01293533,-0.02438898,0.01508459,-0.04970713,-0.00044321,-0.01507511,-0.04394569,-0.01917117,-0.03991311,0.03242642,0.07280398,0.04267042,-0.00790861,-0.03635368,0.00193331,0.07125002,-0.05459208,-0.06392159,0.00490119,0.01444250,0.04826156,0.01507632,0.01256902,0.00713517,0.01752088,0.04491607,-0.00042207,-0.00353037,0.08489394,0.02112931,0.02195734]',E'Slicing\n\nQuickly, though, we realize that there are additional behaviors a client might want. A client might want to be able to specify how many friends they want to fetch—maybe they only want the first two. So we''d want to expose something like this:\n\n```graphql\nquery {\n  hero {\n    name\n    friends(first: 2) {\n      name\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nBut if we just fetched the first two, we might want to paginate through the list as well; once the client fetches the first two friends, they might want to send a second request to ask for the next two friends. How can we enable that behavior?','{"source": "graphql", "version": "1.0", "language": "graphql", "title": "Pagination", "section_title": "paginationx", "url": "https://github.com/graphql/graphql.github.io/blob/source/src/pages/learn/pagination.mdx", "topics": "graphql,paginationx", "categories": "api,query,graphql"}');
